Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/
Object: Government organisation ontology for UK Parliament

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/GovernmentRank
Object: A packaging of ways to describe the rank of a government position. Different bodies have different ways to describe these.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/Position
Object: A position in a group that persists over time which can be occupied by different people at different times e.g. many people have been Foreign Secretary.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/Incumbency
Object: A position held by a person for a period of time. e.g. Philip Hammond occupying the position of Foreign Secretary between two dates.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/isPaid
Object: Used to describe whether an incumbency is paid or not.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/governmentSortOrder
Object: Used to determine how the government chooses to order government organisations. e.g. whether they choose to rank the Foreign Office higher than the Department of Health.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/isLayingPosition
Object: Used to determine if a government position has the authority to lay papers into Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/cabinetRank
Object: Used to capture how the government ranks assorted positions in the cabinet. e.g. whether the Foreign Secretary is ranked above or below the Health Secretary.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/Group
Object: A group of people or a group of groups or a group of people and groups.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/oppositionSortOrder
Object: Used to determine how the official opposition chooses to order government organisations. e.g. whether they choose to rank the Foreign Office higher than the Department of Health.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/AttendsCabinet
Object: Used to determine if the person incumbent in a government position is able to attend cabinet. Possible values are always, never and when required.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/attendsCabinet
Object: Relates a government position to cabinet attendance.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/GovernmentPosition
Object: A position (job) in a government organisation. Note that not all government positions are in government organisations. e.g. Minister without Portfolio is a position outside any department, agency or public body. This is a specialisation of a position from the agency ontology.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/paidToAttendCabinet
Object: Used to determine whether a government position is paid to attend cabinet or not.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/GovernmentIncumbency
Object: An incumbency of a person in a government position. This is a specialisation of an incumbency from the agency ontology.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/hasRank
Object: Relates a government position to assorted ways of describing rank.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/government-organisation/GovernmentOrganisation
Object: Government departments, agencies and public bodies which have responsibility for a specific sector of public administration. Is a specialised type of group.
